data.jamchart_notes: Efficient Pete-led 14-minute journey initiated by his vibesy accompaniment as Rick arpeggiates out of the head section. A soaring synth jam that starts bright and clean morphs into a grittier sawtoothy lead section before landing them into a floating full-band jam with sort of “Scarlet”-islandy motif undergirded by rolling drum fills and well-placed Trevor flair. Rick leads out from there with a punchy attack that twists the tropical theme into a short but assertive closing statement.

data.jamchart_notes: Soak in this Flee as a peaceful gentleness settles in to start. Gorgeous keys by Peter and Rick mimics the style. Like a flowing wave, Trevor and percussion begin increasing tempo and volume as band rises magically only to settle back down in the earlier quiet style, then build back to a fiery finish.

data.jamchart_notes: "Flee" had a pretty good Fall and it all started here. Right when the rocking jam is about to wrap up with the closing guitar solo, this unfinished version instead veers into a delightfully whimsical little passage akin to early 90's Frisell interpreting ragtime music. Peter moves from vibes to clav in a satisfying fashion during a slick transition into "Look Out Cleveland".

data.jamchart_notes: This fluid and vibrant Flee is at its best during the masterful emotive solo Rick guides the first half of the jam with, Peter dancing along with every note in some of his very finest piano accompaniment.

Quickly pivots from easy breezy mode into punchy clav funk. Grows thicker and heavier for several minutes until the band comes up for air and soars into a peaky zone atop Peter's synth drone. Rick's soloing has some serious mojo behind this as Goose blasts through the amazing end of this jam.

data.jamchart_notes: Breaking the longest stretch on the bench since its debut, this "Flee" departs standard play quickly thanks to Rick diving into loops. Creating a hypnotic atmosphere in tandem with the repeating sounds, Peter lays down some piano riffs as we stretch out. Cotter lays in some excellent cymbal washes before upping the tempo and energy while Rick takes us through a seriously blistering peak. Fades atop the toms and slides -> into "Atlas Dogs."
